  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting suspicious financial transactions\n\n2. Key International Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- Increased international cooperation and standardized regulations\n\n3. Major Regulatory Expansions\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Stricter reporting obligations for financial institutions\n- Broader definitions of money laundering offenses\n\n4. Technology-Driven Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Expanded monitoring of online financial transactions\n- Cybercrime prevention mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased transparency requirements\n- Beneficial ownership disclosure mandates\n- Cryptocurrency transaction tracking\n- Enhanced due diligence protocols\n\n6. Global Compliance Frameworks\n- Risk-based approaches\n- Mutual evaluation mechanisms\n- Coordinated international enforcement\n\n7. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Terrorist financing prevention\n- Complex financial network investigations\n- Machine learning and AI-assisted detection\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
